HARDWARE SMOKE PASSED on board 192.168.8.198 (USB-flashed; OTA via port 80 /ota worked for bytes but board did not appear to apply on .138 — investigate as a separate follow-up if you want to re-enable OTA).

Smoke results (all pass):
- Fresh device state: boardId:0, hasActive:false, hasPrevious:false
- POST /boardId?id=1 -> {ok:true,boardId:1}
- Bake v1 (623 bytes worked example from schema doc §8) -> hasActive:true, bytesUsed:623
- Bake v2 (632 bytes, modified motion name) -> hasPrevious:true, bytesUsed:632
- POST /sequences/restore (rollback) -> bytesUsed 632->623
- POST /sequences/restore again -> bytesUsed 623->632 (both slots intact)
- Wrong schemaVersion -> 400 {ok:false,error:unsupported-schema-version}
- Unbalanced braces -> 400 {ok:false,error:unbalanced}
- Missing schemaVersion -> 400 {ok:false,error:missing-schema-version}
- Oversized (5KB) -> 413 {ok:false,error:too-large,limit:4080}
- POST /boardId?id=5 -> 400 {ok:false,error:invalid-id}
- Active slot survived all negative tests
- Reboot persistence: boardId, hasActive, hasPrevious, bytesUsed all preserved

OBSERVATION for servo-3k3 (browser bake pipeline): during EEPROM writes the HTTP response can be dropped while the write itself completes (saw two POST /sequences timeouts that successfully landed the bake anyway). Browser-side bake POST should use ≥10s timeout, and on timeout poll GET /sequences/info to confirm whether the bake actually landed before retrying — a naive retry would create a third bake and lose history.

